'''Charles Bakewell Sherwin''' (9 August 1877 &mdash; 8 June 1950) was an [[England|English]] [[cricket]]er who played first-class cricket for [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] during the 1907 season. 

Sherwin was born  in [[Derby]], the son of Samuel Sherwin, a chemist, and his wife Margaret.<ref>British Census 1881 RG11 3399/62 p1</ref> He played one game for Derbyshire in August 1907 against [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]]. He scored a duck in the first innings and seven in the second when he opened with [[Levi Wright]] who went on to score a century. He was a right-handed batsman and played one first class match with a total score of 7.<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Players/32/32730/32730.html Charles Sherwin at Cricket Archive]</ref>

Sherwin was a photographer with premises at 10 St James Street Derby.<ref>[http://photo-sleuth.blogspot.com/2008_02_01_archive.html Photo-sleuth]</ref>

Sherwin died in Derby at the age of 72. His brother, [[Arthur Sherwin|Arthur]], two years his junior, played for Derbyshire during the 1908 season.

